"Torres-Porras J., Carranza J., Pérez-González J.","Combined effects of drought and density on body and antler size of male Iberian red deer Cervus elaphus hispanicus: Climate change implications",2009,"Wildlife Biology","15","2",,"213","221",,,10.2981/08-059,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-68949099372&partnerID=40&md5=b74a967f4dc732c6e398b65d896094ef","Biology and Ethology Unit, University of Extremadura, E-10071 Cáceres, Spain","Torres-Porras, J., Biology and Ethology Unit, University of Extremadura, E-10071 Cáceres, Spain; Carranza, J., Biology and Ethology Unit, University of Extremadura, E-10071 Cáceres, Spain; Pérez-González, J., Biology and Ethology Unit, University of Extremadura, E-10071 Cáceres, Spain","Hunting management of red deer Cervus elaphus populations may tend to increase population densities to maximise annual yield. Some studies have shown that density and low winter temperatures affect red deer populations in central and northern Europe, but these results cannot be extrapolated to red deer populations in the Mediterranean region where the limiting season is summer instead of winter. The two regions are predicted to experience different climate change effects: while rainfall may increase in northern latitudes, heavier droughts are expected in the Mediterranean region. We studied red deer populations of different densities on 19 hunting estates in southern Spain during two years with contrasting precipitation levels. Our aim was to quantify the combined effects of drought and population density on the development of stags, which is the main economic objective of hunting management in these areas. We found that drought affected body and antler size negatively, and that the effects were more severe in populations of high density. On the basis of our results, we recommend reducing the current densities of red deer in southern Spain to maintain the economic and environmental sustainability of hunting exploitation in the context of global climate change. ©WILDLIFE BIOLOGY.","Cervus elaphus; Density; Drought; Game management; Global climate change; Iberian red deer","Cervus elaphus; Cervus elaphus hispanicus",,,,,,"Alarcos, S., (2007) Consecuencias de las estrategias reproductivas de machos y hembras sobre la morfología, desarrollo y longevidad del ciervo ibérico, , Doctoral thesis, University of Extremadura, 300 pp, In Spanish; Albon, S.D., Clutton-Brock, T.H., Guinness, F.E., Early development and population dynamics in red deer. II. Density independent effects and cohort variation (1987) Journal of Animal Ecology, 56, pp. 69-81; Azorit, C., Analla, M., Carrasco, R., Muñoz-Cobo, J., Influence of age and environment on antler traits in Spanish red deer (Cervus elaphus hispanicus). - (2002) Zeitschrift für Jagdwissenschaft, 48, pp. 137-144; Bonenfant, C., Gaillard, J.-M., Klein, F., Loison, A., Sex- and age-dependent effects of population density on life history traits of red deer (Cervus elaphus) in a temperate forest (2002) Ecography, 25, pp. 446-458; Bugalho, M.N., Milne, J.A., The composition of the diet of red deer (Cervus elaphus) in a Mediterranean environment: A case of summer nutritional constraint? (2003) Forest Ecology and Management, 181 (1-2), pp. 23-29; Carranza, J., Female attraction by males versus sites in territorial rutting red deer (1995) Animal Behaviour, 50, pp. 445-453; Carranza, J., Aplicaciones de la Etologia al manejo de las poblaciones de ciervo en el suroeste de la Península Ibérica: Producción y conservación. (1999) Etologia, 7, pp. 5-18. , In Spanish; Carranza, J., Alvarez, F., Redondo, T., Territoriality as a mating strategy in red deer (1990) Animal Behaviour, 40, pp. 79-88; Carranza, J., Fernández-Llario, P., Gomendio, M., Correlates of territoriality in rutting red deer (1996) Ethology, 102, pp. 793-805; Clutton-Brock, T.H., Albon, S.D., Winter mortality in red deer (Cervus elaphus) (1982) Journal of Zoology, 198 (4), pp. 515-519; Clutton-Brock, T.H., Albon, S